ly Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Americo, Cesareo, Fernando, Ines, Javier, Jose, Marcos.  Portuguese Henrique.  Italian Antonio, Gino, Olindo, Silvio, Vito.  Dutch Andries.","Italian: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mare</i> ‘sea’.","English: variant of   Mear  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marucci","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Antonio, Silvio, Angelo, Carmela, Domenic, Donato, Egidio, Guido, Licinio, Lorenzo, Luciano.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Maruccio</i>, a pet form of   Mare   or   Mari  ."]},{"name":"Marelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Giuseppe, Angelo, Dante.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Mare  ."]},{"name":"Mear","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Franz, Helmut, Wilhelm, Erwin, Gerhard, Heinz, Ilse, Lorenz, Wolfgang.","English (Staffordshire): post-medieval form of <b>Mear</b>, which is either a topographic name, from Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘pond, pool’ (Old English <i>mere</i>) or Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘boundary’ (Old English <i>(ge)mǣre</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places with names derived from these terms, such as Mere (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Wiltshire), Meir in Caverswall (Staffordshire), and Meare (Somerset).","English: occupational name for a physician, from Old French <i>mire</i>, Middle English <i>mire</i>, <i>meir</i>, <i>meyre</i>, originally synonymous with   Myer  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Grace’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Nicholas de la Mare was born about 1190, in Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Gracia Meysy. He died on 25 July 1229, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1190–25 July 1229":"umbes 1190–25. juuli 1229","1202–1261":"1202–1261","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1190":"1190","25 July 1229":"25. juuli 1229","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1202":"1202","1256":"1256","1261":"1261","1229":"1229","Nunney,Somerset,England.":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1190–25 July 1229":"noin 1190–25. heinäkuuta 1229","1202–1261":"1202–1261","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1190":"1190","25 July 1229":"25. heinäkuuta 1229","about 1190":"noin 1190","1202":"1202","1256":"1256","1261":"1261","1229":"1229","Nunney,Somerset,England.":"Nunney, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1190–25 July 1229":"enviro